<TEXT>
Three Soviet technicians will take a look 
at the town of Magna to get a general feeling for the community 
where their countrymen could be stationed if the Intermediate 
Nuclear Forces treaty is ratified 
Dave Porter a spokesman for Sen Orrin Hatch RUtah said 
State Department officials had confirmed the Soviet team was 
expected in Utah today for a twoday review An American contingent 
was to conduct a similar tour in the Soviet Union 
Porter said the Soviet technicians planned to tour Magna about 
25 miles southwest of Salt Lake City this afternoon He said 
specific details were not available 
Magna population 8500 is a few miles from the Hercules 
Bacchus West plant Up to 30 Soviet inspectors may establish a 
compound near the plant if the Senate ratifies the INF treaty 
signed Dec 7 by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail 
Gorbachev 
The treaty would eliminate intermediaterange nuclear weaponry 
in both countries arsenals 
The countries inspection teams could be in place within 60 days 
of the treatys ratifications officials say 
The Soviets would monitor Hercules which developed motors for 
the Pershing II missiles banned under the treaty from 1979 to 
1987 
The Soviet technicians will be accompanied by four members of 
the State Departments OnSite Inspection Agency Porter said 
Today the Soviets will make a very general visit to Magna 
It will just be the town the stores just to get a feeling for the 
area he said 
On Thursday the three technicians will conduct a similar tour 
of Salt Lake City and then leave Friday Porter said He said no 
news conferences or statements were planned 
The Soviet and American advance teams will meet in Moscow a week 
after the tours to discuss housing travel and other arrangements 
Hatchs office said 
Pershing II missile motors no longer are built at Hercules but 
the company has a contract for thirdstage motors for the 
intercontinental MX missile 
